# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: perl-docs
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Perl has three built-in data types: scalars, arrays of scalars, and associative arrays of scalars, known as "hashes".
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A scalar is a single string (of any size, limited only by the available memory), number, or a reference to something (which will be discussed in perlref).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Normal arrays are ordered lists of scalars indexed by number, starting with 0.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Hashes are unordered collections of scalar values indexed by their associated string key.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Values are usually referred to by name, or through a named reference.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The first character of the name tells you to what sort of data structure it refers.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The rest of the name tells you the particular value to which it refers.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Usually this name is a single *identifier*, that is, a string beginning with a letter or underscore, and containing letters, underscores, and digits.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In some cases, it may be a chain of identifiers, separated by `::` (or by the deprecated `'`); all but the last are interpreted as names of packages, to locate the namespace in which to look up the final identifier (see "Packages" in perlmod for details).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] For a more in-depth discussion on identifiers, see "Identifier parsing".
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] It's possible to substitute for a simple identifier, an expression that produces a reference to the value at runtime.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This is described in more detail below and in perlref.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] It is legal, but not recommended, to separate a variable's sigil from its name by space and/or tab characters.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Perl also has its own built-in variables whose names don't follow these rules.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] They have strange names so they don't accidentally collide with one of your normal variables.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Strings that match parenthesized parts of a regular expression are saved under names containing only digits after the `$` (see perlop and perlre).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In addition, several special variables that provide windows into the inner working of Perl have names containing punctuation characters.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Scalar values are always named with the sigil `'$'`, even when referring to a scalar that is part of an array or a hash.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The `'$'` symbol works semantically like the English word "the" in that it indicates a single value is expected.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Entire arrays (and slices of arrays and hashes) are denoted by the sigil `'@'`, which works much as the word "these" or "those" does in English, in that it indicates multiple values are expected.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In addition, subroutines are named with an initial sigil `'&'`, though this is optional when unambiguous, just as the word "do" is often redundant in English.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Symbol table entries can be named with an initial `'*'`, but you don't really care about that yet (if ever :-).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Every variable type has its own namespace, as do several non-variable identifiers.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This means that you can, without fear of conflict, use the same name for a scalar variable, an array, or a hash--or, for that matter, for a filehandle, a directory handle, a subroutine name, a format name, or a label.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This means that $foo and @foo are two different variables.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] It also means that `$foo[1]` is a part of @foo, not a part of $foo.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This may seem a bit weird, but that's okay, because it is weird.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Because variable references always start with the sigils `'$'`, `'@'`, or `'%'`, the "reserved" words aren't in fact reserved with respect to variable names.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] They *are* reserved with respect to labels and filehandles, however, which don't have an initial special character.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You can't have a filehandle named "log", for instance.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Hint: you could say `open(LOG,'logfile')` rather than `open(log,'logfile')`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Using uppercase filehandles also improves readability and protects you from conflict with future reserved words.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Case *is* significant--"FOO", "Foo", and "foo" are all different names.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Names that start with a letter or underscore may also contain digits and underscores.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] It is possible to replace such an alphanumeric name with an expression that returns a reference to the appropriate type.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Names that start with a digit may contain only more digits.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Names that do not start with a letter, underscore, digit or a caret are limited to one character, e.g., `$%` or `$$`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] (Most of these one character names have a predefined significance to Perl.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] For instance, `$$` is the current process id.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Up until Perl 5.18, the actual rules of what a valid identifier was were a bit fuzzy.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] However, in general, anything defined here should work on previous versions of Perl, while the opposite -- edge cases that work in previous versions, but aren't defined here -- probably won't work on newer versions.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] As an important side note, please note that the following only applies to bareword identifiers as found in Perl source code, not identifiers introduced through symbolic references, which have much fewer restrictions.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] That is, a "start" character followed by any number of "continue" characters.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Perl requires every character in an identifier to also match `\w` (this prevents some problematic cases); and Perl additionally accepts identifier names beginning with an underscore.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] That is, any word character in the ASCII range, as long as the first character is not a digit.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] There is one package separator in Perl: A double colon (`::`).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Normal identifiers can start or end with a double colon, and can contain several parts delimited by double colons.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Previously you could use `'` as a package separator, this was removed in Perl 5.42.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Additionally, if the identifier is preceded by a sigil -- that is, if the identifier is part of a variable name -- it may optionally be enclosed in braces.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Meanwhile, special identifiers don't follow the above rules; For the most part, all of the identifiers in this category have a special meaning given by Perl.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Because they have special parsing rules, these generally can't be fully-qualified.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A sigil followed by a single character matching the `\p{POSIX_Punct}` property, like `$!` or `%+`, except the character `"{"` doesn't work.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A sigil, followed by a caret and any one of the characters `[][A-Z^_?\]`, like `$^V` or `$^]`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Similar to the above, a sigil, followed by bareword text in braces, where the first character is a caret.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The next character is any one of the characters `[][A-Z^_?\]`, followed by ASCII word characters.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A sigil, followed by any single character in the range `[\xA1-\xAC\xAE-\xFF]` when not under `"use utf8"`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] (Under `"use utf8"`, the normal identifier rules given earlier in this section apply.) Use of non-graphic characters (the C1 controls, the NO-BREAK SPACE, and the SOFT HYPHEN) has been disallowed since v5.26.0.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The use of the other characters is unwise, as these are all reserved to have special meaning to Perl, and none of them currently do have special meaning, though this could change without notice.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This is a combination of the previous two forms.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] It is valid only when not under `"use utf8"` (normal identifier rules apply when under `"use utf8"`).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The form is a sigil, followed by text in braces, where the first character is any one of the characters in the range `[\x80-\xFF]` followed by ASCII word characters up to the trailing brace.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The same caveats as the previous form apply: The non-graphic characters are no longer allowed with "use utf8", it is unwise to use this form at all, and utf8ness makes a big difference.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Prior to Perl v5.24, non-graphical ASCII control characters were also allowed in some situations; this had been deprecated since v5.20.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The interpretation of operations and values in Perl sometimes depends on the requirements of the context around the operation or value.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] There are two major contexts: list and scalar.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Certain operations return list values in contexts wanting a list, and scalar values otherwise.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If this is true of an operation it will be mentioned in the documentation for that operation.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In other words, Perl overloads certain operations based on whether the expected return value is singular or plural.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Some words in English work this way, like "fish" and "sheep".
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In a reciprocal fashion, an operation provides either a scalar or a list context to each of its arguments.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] the integer operation provides scalar context for the <> operator, which responds by reading one line from STDIN and passing it back to the integer operation, which will then find the integer value of that line and return that.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] then the sort operation provides list context for <>, which will proceed to read every line available up to the end of file, and pass that list of lines back to the sort routine, which will then sort those lines and return them as a list to whatever the context of the sort was.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Assignment is a little bit special in that it uses its left argument to determine the context for the right argument.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Assignment to a scalar evaluates the right-hand side in scalar context, while assignment to an array or hash evaluates the righthand side in list context.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Assignment to a list (or slice, which is just a list anyway) also evaluates the right-hand side in list context.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] When you use the `use warnings` pragma or Perl's **-w** command-line option, you may see warnings about useless uses of constants or functions in "void context".
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Void context just means the value has been discarded, such as a statement containing only `"fred";` or `getpwuid(0);`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] It still counts as scalar context for functions that care whether or not they're being called in list context.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] User-defined subroutines may choose to care whether they are being called in a void, scalar, or list context.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Most subroutines do not need to bother, though.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] That's because both scalars and lists are automatically interpolated into lists.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] See "wantarray" in perlfunc for how you would dynamically discern your function's calling context.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] All data in Perl is a scalar, an array of scalars, or a hash of scalars.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A scalar may contain one single value in any of three different flavors: a number, a string, or a reference.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In general, conversion from one form to another is transparent.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Although a scalar may not directly hold multiple values, it may contain a reference to an array or hash which in turn contains multiple values.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Scalars aren't necessarily one thing or another.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] There's no place to declare a scalar variable to be of type "string", type "number", type "reference", or anything else.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Because of the automatic conversion of scalars, operations that return scalars don't need to care (and in fact, cannot care) whether their caller is looking for a string, a number, or a reference.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Perl is a contextually polymorphic language whose scalars can be strings, numbers, or references (which includes objects).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Although strings and numbers are considered pretty much the same thing for nearly all purposes, references are strongly-typed, uncastable pointers with builtin reference-counting and destructor invocation.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A scalar value is interpreted as FALSE in the Boolean sense if it is undefined, the null string or the number 0 (or its string equivalent, "0"), and TRUE if it is anything else.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The Boolean context is just a special kind of scalar context where no conversion to a string or a number is ever performed.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Negation of a true value by `!` or `not` returns a special false value.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] When evaluated as a string it is treated as `""`, but as a number, it is treated as 0.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Most Perl operators that return true or false behave this way.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] There are actually two varieties of null strings (sometimes referred to as "empty" strings), a defined one and an undefined one.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The defined version is just a string of length zero, such as `""`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The undefined version is the value that indicates that there is no real value for something, such as when there was an error, or at end of file, or when you refer to an uninitialized variable or element of an array or hash.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Although in early versions of Perl, an undefined scalar could become defined when first used in a place expecting a defined value, this no longer happens except for rare cases of autovivification as explained in perlref.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You can use the defined() operator to determine whether a scalar value is defined (this has no meaning on arrays or hashes), and the undef() operator to produce an undefined value.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] To find out whether a given string is a valid non-zero number, it's sometimes enough to test it against both numeric 0 and also lexical "0" (although this will cause noises if warnings are on).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] That method may be best because otherwise you won't treat IEEE notations like `NaN` or `Infinity` properly.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] At other times, you might prefer to determine whether string data can be used numerically by calling the POSIX::strtod() function or by inspecting your string with a regular expression (as documented in perlre).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The length of an array is a scalar value.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You may find the length of array @days by evaluating `$#days`, as in **csh**.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] However, this isn't the length of the array; it's the subscript of the last element, which is a different value since there is ordinarily a 0th element.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Assigning to `$#days` actually changes the length of the array.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Shortening an array this way destroys intervening values.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Lengthening an array that was previously shortened does not recover values that were in those elements.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You can also gain some minuscule measure of efficiency by pre-extending an array that is going to get big.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You can also extend an array by assigning to an element that is off the end of the array.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You can truncate an array down to nothing by assigning the null list () to it.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If you evaluate an array in scalar context, it returns the length of the array.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If you evaluate a hash in scalar context, it returns a false value if the hash is empty.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If there are any key/value pairs, it returns a true value.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A more precise definition is version dependent.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Prior to Perl 5.25 the value returned was a string consisting of the number of used buckets and the number of allocated buckets, separated by a slash.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This is pretty much useful only to find out whether Perl's internal hashing algorithm is performing poorly on your data set.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] For example, you stick 10,000 things in a hash, but evaluating %HASH in scalar context reveals `"1/16"`, which means only one out of sixteen buckets has been touched, and presumably contains all 10,000 of your items.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] As of Perl 5.25 the return was changed to be the count of keys in the hash.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If you need access to the old behavior you can use `Hash::Util::bucket_ratio()` instead.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If a tied hash is evaluated in scalar context, the `SCALAR` method is called (with a fallback to `FIRSTKEY`).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You can preallocate space for a hash by assigning to the keys() function.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You are allowed to use underscores (underbars) in numeric literals between digits for legibility (but not multiple underscores in a row: `23__500` is not legal; `23_500` is).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You could, for example, group binary digits by threes (as for a Unix-style mode argument such as 0b110_100_100) or by fours (to represent nibbles, as in 0b1010_0110) or in other groups.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] String literals are usually delimited by either single or double quotes.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] They work much like quotes in the standard Unix shells: double-quoted string literals are subject to backslash and variable substitution; single-quoted strings are not (except for `\'` and `\\`).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The usual C-style backslash rules apply for making characters such as newline, tab, etc., as well as some more exotic forms.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] See "Quote and Quote-like Operators" in perlop for a list.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Hexadecimal, octal, or binary, representations in string literals (e.g.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] '0xff') are not automatically converted to their integer representation.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The hex() and oct() functions make these conversions for you.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] See "hex" in perlfunc and "oct" in perlfunc for more details.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Hexadecimal floating point can start just like a hexadecimal literal, and it can be followed by an optional fractional hexadecimal part, but it must be followed by `p`, an optional sign, and a power of two.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The format is useful for accurately presenting floating point values, avoiding conversions to or from decimal floating point, and therefore avoiding possible loss in precision.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Notice that while most current platforms use the 64-bit IEEE 754 floating point, not all do.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Another potential source of (low-order) differences are the floating point rounding modes, which can differ between CPUs, operating systems, and compilers, and which Perl doesn't control.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Octal and binary floating point numbers use the same format as hexadecimal floating point numbers, but limited to binary and octal digits, respectively.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You can also embed newlines directly in your strings, i.e., they can end on a different line than they begin.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This is nice, but if you forget your trailing quote, the error will not be reported until Perl finds another line containing the quote character, which may be much further on in the script.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Variable substitution inside strings is limited to scalar variables, arrays, and array or hash slices.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] There is no double interpolation in Perl, so the `$100` is left as is.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] By default floating point numbers substituted inside strings use the dot (".") as the decimal separator.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If `use locale` is in effect, and POSIX::setlocale() has been called, the character used for the decimal separator is affected by the LC_NUMERIC locale.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] As in some shells, you can enclose the variable name in braces as a demarcator to disambiguate it from following alphanumerics and underscores or other text.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Without the braces, Perl would have looked for a $whospeak, a `$who::0`, and a `$who's` variable.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The last two would be the $0 and the $s variables in the (presumably) non-existent package `who`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In fact, a simple identifier within such curly braces is forced to be a string, and likewise within a hash subscript.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Our earlier example, `$days{'Feb'}` can be written as `$days{Feb}` and the quotes will be assumed automatically.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] But anything more complicated in the subscript will be interpreted as an expression.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] There is a similar problem with interpolation with text that looks like array or hash access notation.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] would attempt to access index 1 of an array named `@who`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This notation also applies to more complex variable descriptions, such as array or hash access with subscripts.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A similar result may be derived by using a backslash on the first character of the subscript or package notation that is not part of the variable you want to access.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] however for some special variables (multi character caret variables) the demarcated form using curly braces is the **only** way you can reference the variable at all, and the only way you can access a subscript of the variable via interpolation.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Consider the magic array `@{^CAPTURE}` which is populated by the regex engine with the contents of all of the capture buffers in a pattern (see perlvar and perlre).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Saying `@^CAPTURE` is a syntax error, so it **must** be referenced as `@{^CAPTURE}`, and to access one of its elements in normal code you would write `${^CAPTURE}[1]`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] However when interpolating in a string `"${^CAPTURE}[1]"` would be equivalent to `${^CAPTURE} .
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] "[1]"`, which does not even refer to the same variable!
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Thus the subscripts must **also** be placed **inside** of the braces: `"${^CAPTURE[1]}"`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The demarcated form using curly braces can be used with all the different types of variable access, including array and hash slices.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Floating point values include the special values `Inf` and `NaN`, for infinity and not-a-number.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The infinity is the result of certain math operations that overflow the floating point range, like 9**9**9.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The not-a-number is the result when the result is undefined or unrepresentable.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Though note that you cannot get `NaN` from some common "undefined" or "out-of-range" operations like dividing by zero, or square root of a negative number, since Perl generates fatal errors for those.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The infinity and not-a-number have their own special arithmetic rules.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The general rule is that they are "contagious": `Inf` plus one is `Inf`, and `NaN` plus one is `NaN`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Where things get interesting is when you combine infinities and not-a-numbers: `Inf` minus `Inf` and `Inf` divided by `Inf` are `NaN` (while `Inf` plus `Inf` is `Inf` and `Inf` times `Inf` is `Inf`).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] `NaN` is also curious in that it does not equal any number, *including* itself: `NaN` != `NaN`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Perl doesn't understand `Inf` and `NaN` as numeric literals, but you can have them as strings, and Perl will convert them as needed: "Inf" + 1.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Note that on input (string to number) Perl accepts `Inf` and `NaN` in many forms.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Case is ignored, and the Win32-specific forms like `1.#INF` are understood, but on output the values are normalized to `Inf` and `NaN`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A literal of the form `v1.20.300.4000` is parsed as a string composed of characters with the specified ordinals.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This form, known as v-strings, provides an alternative, more readable way to construct strings, rather than use the somewhat less readable interpolation form `"\x{1}\x{14}\x{12c}\x{fa0}"`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This is useful for representing Unicode strings, and for comparing version "numbers" using the string comparison operators, `cmp`, `gt`, `lt` etc.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If there are two or more dots in the literal, the leading `v` may be omitted.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Such literals are accepted by both `require` and `use` for doing a version check.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Note that using the v-strings for IPv4 addresses is not portable unless you also use the inet_aton()/inet_ntoa() routines of the Socket package.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Note that since Perl 5.8.1 the single-number v-strings (like `v65`) are not v-strings before the `=>` operator (which is usually used to separate a hash key from a hash value); instead they are interpreted as literal strings ('v65').
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] They were v-strings from Perl 5.6.0 to Perl 5.8.0, but that caused more confusion and breakage than good.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Multi-number v-strings like `v65.66` and `65.66.67` continue to be v-strings always.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The special literals __FILE__, __LINE__, and __PACKAGE__ represent the current filename, line number, and package name at that point in your program. __SUB__ gives a reference to the current subroutine.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] They may be used only as separate tokens; they will not be interpolated into strings.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If there is no current package (due to an empty `package;` directive), __PACKAGE__ is the undefined value.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] (But the empty `package;` is no longer supported, as of version 5.10.) Outside of a subroutine, __SUB__ is the undefined value. __SUB__ is only available in 5.16 or higher, and only with a `use v5.16` or `use feature "current_sub"` declaration.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The two control characters ^D and ^Z, and the tokens __END__ and __DATA__ may be used to indicate the logical end of the script before the actual end of file.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Any following text is ignored by the interpreter unless read by the program as described below.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Text after __DATA__ may be read via the filehandle `PACKNAME::DATA`, where `PACKNAME` is the package that was current when the __DATA__ token was encountered.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The filehandle is left open pointing to the line after __DATA__.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The program should `close DATA` when it is done reading from it.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The `DATA` file handle by default has whatever PerlIO layers were in place when Perl read the file to parse the source.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Normally that means that the file is being read bytewise, as if it were encoded in Latin-1, but there are two major ways for it to be otherwise.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Firstly, if the `__END__`/`__DATA__` token is in the scope of a `use utf8` pragma then the `DATA` handle will be in UTF-8 mode.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] And secondly, if the source is being read from perl's standard input then the `DATA` file handle is actually aliased to the `STDIN` file handle, and may be in UTF-8 mode because of the `PERL_UNICODE` environment variable or perl's command-line switches.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] See SelfLoader for more description of __DATA__, and an example of its use.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Note that you cannot read from the DATA filehandle in a BEGIN block: the BEGIN block is executed as soon as it is seen (during compilation), at which point the corresponding __DATA__ (or __END__) token has not yet been seen.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A word that has no other interpretation in the grammar will be treated as if it were a quoted string.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] As with filehandles and labels, a bareword that consists entirely of lowercase letters risks conflict with future reserved words, and if you use the `use warnings` pragma or the **-w** switch, Perl will warn you about any such words.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Perl limits barewords (like identifiers) to about 250 characters.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Future versions of Perl are likely to eliminate these arbitrary limitations.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Some people may wish to outlaw barewords entirely.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] then any bareword that would NOT be interpreted as a subroutine call produces a compile-time error instead.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The restriction lasts to the end of the enclosing block.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] An inner block may countermand this by saying `no strict 'subs'`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Arrays and slices are interpolated into double-quoted strings by joining the elements with the delimiter specified in the `$"` variable (`$LIST_SEPARATOR` if "use English;" is specified), space by default.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Within search patterns (which also undergo double-quotish substitution) there is an unfortunate ambiguity: Is `/$foo[bar]/` to be interpreted as `/${foo}[bar]/` (where `[bar]` is a character class for the regular expression) or as `/${foo[bar]}/` (where `[bar]` is the subscript to array @foo)?
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If @foo doesn't otherwise exist, then it's obviously a character class.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If @foo exists, Perl takes a good guess about `[bar]`, and is almost always right.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If it does guess wrong, or if you're just plain paranoid, you can force the correct interpretation with curly braces as above.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If you're looking for the information on how to use here-documents, which used to be here, that's been moved to "Quote and Quote-like Operators" in perlop.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In a context not requiring a list value, the value of what appears to be a list literal is simply the value of the final element, as with the C comma operator.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] assigns the value of variable $bar to the scalar variable $foo.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] LISTs do automatic interpolation of sublists.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] That is, when a LIST is evaluated, each element of the list is evaluated in list context, and the resulting list value is interpolated into LIST just as if each individual element were a member of LIST.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] contains all the elements of @foo followed by all the elements of @bar, followed by all the elements returned by the subroutine named SomeSub called in list context, followed by the key/value pairs of %glarch.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] To make a list reference that does *NOT* interpolate, see perlref.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Interpolating it in a list has no effect.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Similarly, interpolating an array with no elements is the same as if no array had been interpolated at that point.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This interpolation combines with the facts that the opening and closing parentheses are optional (except when necessary for precedence) and lists may end with an optional comma to mean that multiple commas within lists are legal syntax.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The list `1,,3` is a concatenation of two lists, `1,` and `3`, the first of which ends with that optional comma.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A list value may also be subscripted like a normal array.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You must put the list in parentheses to avoid ambiguity.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] An exception to this is that you may assign to `undef` in a list.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] As of Perl 5.22, you can also use `(undef)x2` instead of `undef, undef`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] When you assign a list of scalars to an array, all previous values in that array are wiped out and the number of elements in the array will now be equal to the number of elements in the right-hand list -- the list from which assignment was made.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The array will automatically resize itself to precisely accommodate each element in the right-hand list.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] When, however, you assign a list of scalars to another list of scalars, the results differ according to whether the left-hand list -- the list being assigned to -- has the same, more or fewer elements than the right-hand list.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If the number of scalars in the left-hand list is less than that in the right-hand list, the "extra" scalars in the right-hand list will simply not be assigned.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] If the number of scalars in the left-hand list is greater than that in the left-hand list, the "missing" scalars will become undefined.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This is handy when you want to do a list assignment in a Boolean context, because most list functions return a null list when finished, which when assigned produces a 0, which is interpreted as FALSE.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] It's also the source of a useful idiom for executing a function or performing an operation in list context and then counting the number of return values, by assigning to an empty list and then using that assignment in scalar context.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] will place into $count the number of digit groups found in $string.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This happens because the pattern match is in list context (since it is being assigned to the empty list), and will therefore return a list of all matching parts of the string.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The list assignment in scalar context will translate that into the number of elements (here, the number of times the pattern matched) and assign that to $count.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] would not have worked, since a pattern match in scalar context will only return true or false, rather than a count of matches.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] You can actually put an array or hash anywhere in the list, but the first one in the list will soak up all the values, and anything after it will become undefined.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] This may be useful in a my() or local().
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] While literal lists and named arrays are often interchangeable, that's not the case for hashes.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Just because you can subscript a list value like a normal array does not mean that you can subscript a list value as a hash.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Likewise, hashes included as parts of other lists (including parameters lists and return lists from functions) always flatten out into key/value pairs.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] That's why it's good to use references sometimes.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] It is often more readable to use the `=>` operator between key/value pairs.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The `=>` operator is mostly just a more visually distinctive synonym for a comma, but it also arranges for its left-hand operand to be interpreted as a string if it's a bareword that would be a legal simple identifier.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] `=>` doesn't quote compound identifiers, that contain double colons.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Note that just because a hash is initialized in that order doesn't mean that it comes out in that order.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] See "sort" in perlfunc for examples of how to arrange for an output ordering.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] An array can be accessed one scalar at a time by specifying a dollar sign (`$`), then the name of the array (without the leading `@`), then the subscript inside square brackets.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] A negative subscript retrieves its value from the end.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] In our example, `$myarray[-1]` would have been 5000, and `$myarray[-2]` would have been 500.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Hash subscripts are similar, only instead of square brackets curly brackets are used.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] Multidimensional arrays may be emulated by subscripting a hash with a list.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The elements of the list are joined with the subscript separator (see "$;" in perlvar).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p01] The default subscript separator is "\034", the same as SUBSEP in **awk**.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] A slice accesses several elements of a list, an array, or a hash simultaneously using a list of subscripts.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] It's more convenient than writing out the individual elements as a list of separate scalar values.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Since you can assign to a list of variables, you can also assign to an array or hash slice.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Since changing a slice changes the original array or hash that it's slicing, a `foreach` construct will alter some--or even all--of the values of the array or hash.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] As a special exception, when you slice a list (but not an array or a hash), if the list evaluates to empty, then taking a slice of that empty list will always yield the empty list in turn.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] As noted earlier in this document, the scalar sense of list assignment is the number of elements on the right-hand side of the assignment.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] The null list contains no elements, so when the password file is exhausted, the result is 0, not 2.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Slices in scalar context return the last item of the slice.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] If you're confused about why you use an `'@'` there on a hash slice instead of a `'%'`, think of it like this.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] The type of bracket (square or curly) governs whether it's an array or a hash being looked at.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] On the other hand, the leading symbol (`'$'` or `'@'`) on the array or hash indicates whether you are getting back a singular value (a scalar) or a plural one (a list).
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] However, the result of such a slice cannot be localized or assigned to.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] These are otherwise very much consistent with hash slices using the @ symbol.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Note that calling `delete` on array values is strongly discouraged.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Perl uses an internal type called a *typeglob* to hold an entire symbol table entry.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] The type prefix of a typeglob is a `*`, because it represents all types.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] This used to be the preferred way to pass arrays and hashes by reference into a function, but now that we have real references, this is seldom needed.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] The main use of typeglobs in modern Perl is to create symbol table aliases.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] makes $this an alias for $that, @this an alias for @that, %this an alias for %that, &this an alias for &that, etc.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] temporarily makes $Here::blue an alias for $There::green, but doesn't make @Here::blue an alias for @There::green, or %Here::blue an alias for %There::green, etc.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] See "Symbol Tables" in perlmod for more examples of this.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Strange though this may seem, this is the basis for the whole module import/export system.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Another use for typeglobs is to pass filehandles into a function or to create new filehandles.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] See perlsub for examples of using these as indirect filehandles in functions.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Typeglobs are also a way to create a local filehandle using the local() operator.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] These last until their block is exited, but may be passed back.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Now that we have the `*foo{THING}` notation, typeglobs aren't used as much for filehandle manipulations, although they're still needed to pass brand new file and directory handles into or out of functions.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] That's because `*HANDLE{IO}` only works if HANDLE has already been used as a handle.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] In other words, `*FH` must be used to create new symbol table entries; `*foo{THING}` cannot.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] All functions that are capable of creating filehandles (open(), opendir(), pipe(), socketpair(), sysopen(), socket(), and accept()) automatically create an anonymous filehandle if the handle passed to them is an uninitialized scalar variable.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] This allows the constructs such as `open(my $fh, ...)` and `open(local $fh,...)` to be used to create filehandles that will conveniently be closed automatically when the scope ends, provided there are no other references to them.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Note that if an initialized scalar variable is used instead the result is different: `my $fh='zzz'; open($fh, ...)` is equivalent to `open( *{'zzz'}, ...)`.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] `use strict 'refs'` forbids such practice.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] Another way to create anonymous filehandles is with the Symbol module or with the IO::Handle module and its ilk.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] These modules have the advantage of not hiding different types of the same name during the local().
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] See the bottom of "open" in perlfunc for an example.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] See perlvar for a description of Perl's built-in variables and a discussion of legal variable names.
[src:perl-docs/perldata-p02] See perlref, perlsub, and "Symbol Tables" in perlmod for more discussion on typeglobs and the `*foo{THING}` syntax.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] This document is intended to give you a quick overview of the Perl programming language, along with pointers to further documentation.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] It is intended as a "bootstrap" guide for those who are new to the language, and provides just enough information for you to be able to read other peoples' Perl and understand roughly what it's doing, or write your own simple scripts.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] This introductory document does not aim to be complete.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] It does not even aim to be entirely accurate.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] In some cases perfection has been sacrificed in the goal of getting the general idea across.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You are *strongly* advised to follow this introduction with more information from the full Perl manual, the table of contents to which can be found in perltoc.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Throughout this document you'll see references to other parts of the Perl documentation.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You can read that documentation using the `perldoc` command or whatever method you're using to read this document.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Throughout Perl's documentation, you'll find numerous examples intended to help explain the discussed features.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Please keep in mind that many of them are code fragments rather than complete programs.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] These examples often reflect the style and preference of the author of that piece of the documentation, and may be briefer than a corresponding line of code in a real program.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Except where otherwise noted, you should assume that `use strict` and `use warnings` statements appear earlier in the "program", and that any variables used have already been declared, even if those declarations have been omitted to make the example easier to read.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Do note that the examples have been written by many different authors over a period of several decades.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Styles and techniques will therefore differ, although some effort has been made to not vary styles too widely in the same sections.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Do not consider one style to be better than others - "There's More Than One Way To Do It" is one of Perl's mottos.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] After all, in your journey as a programmer, you are likely to encounter different styles.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Perl is a general-purpose programming language originally developed for text manipulation and now used for a wide range of tasks including system administration, web development, network programming, GUI development, and more.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The language is intended to be practical (easy to use, efficient, complete) rather than beautiful (tiny, elegant, minimal).
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Its major features are that it's easy to use, supports both procedural and object-oriented (OO) programming, has powerful built-in support for text processing, and has one of the world's most impressive collections of third-party modules.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Different definitions of Perl are given in perl, perlfaq1 and no doubt other places.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] From this we can determine that Perl is different things to different people, but that lots of people think it's at least worth writing about.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] ... and run the script as */path/to/script.pl*.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Of course, it'll need to be executable first, so `chmod 755 script.pl` (under Unix).
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] (This start line assumes you have the **env** program.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You can also put directly the path to your perl executable, like in `#!/usr/bin/perl`).
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] For more information, including instructions for other platforms such as Windows, read perlrun.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The two additional lines request from perl to catch various common problems in your code.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] They check different things so you need both.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] A potential problem caught by `use strict;` will cause your code to stop immediately when it is encountered, while `use warnings;` will merely give a warning (like the command-line switch **-w**) and let your code run.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] To read more about them, check their respective manual pages at strict and warnings.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] A Perl script or program consists of one or more statements.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] These statements are simply written in the script in a straightforward fashion.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] There is no need to have a `main()` function or anything of that kind.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You can use parentheses for functions' arguments or omit them according to your personal taste.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] They are only required occasionally to clarify issues of precedence.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] More detailed information about Perl syntax can be found in perlsyn.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You may have noticed the strange character string <$name> above.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] That denotes a variable, which is generally pronounced as "name".
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The dollar sign is called a "sigil", and indicates that "name" is a variable.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Unlike many other computer languages where variables are just strings of typically only alphabetic and numeric characters, all Perl variables are preceded by a sigil.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Perl has three main variable types: scalars, arrays, and hashes.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The particular sigil used for a variable name indicates the type of that variable.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] We've already seen the dollar sign used as a sigil, `$name`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The dollar sign indicates this variable is a scalar.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Scalar values can be strings, integers or floating point numbers, and Perl will automatically convert between them as required.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You have to declare them using the `my` keyword the first time you use them.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Perl defines a number of special scalars with short names, often single punctuation marks or digits.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] These variables are used for all kinds of purposes, and are documented in perlvar.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The only one you need to know about for now is `$_` which is the "default variable".
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] It's used as the default argument to a number of functions in Perl, and it's set implicitly by certain looping constructs.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Each of these arrays is an aggregation of individual values.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] In Perl, scalars are always referenced with the `$` sigil.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Thus we wrote `$animals[0]` above to get the 0th scalar variable inside the `@animals` array.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The square brackets `[...]` indicate that it is an array that we are getting the value from.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] This is a major point of confusion for newcomers to Perl.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] When you are looking at a single value, you need to use `$`, even though that value is part of a larger aggregation.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You might be tempted to use `$#array + 1` to tell you how many items there are in an array.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The elements we're getting from the array start with a `$` because we're getting just a single value out of the array; you ask for a scalar, you get a scalar.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] We used the `@` sigil here because we want multiple values; `$` is reserved for referencing single values.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] There are a couple of special arrays too, such as `@ARGV` (the command line arguments to your script) and `@_` (the arguments passed to a subroutine).
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] A hash represents a set of key/value pairs.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Note again the use of the `$` sigil to access a single hash element.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The curly braces `{...}` indicate that it is an hash that we are getting the value from.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Note again that multiple values use the sigil `@`, and single ones use `$`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You can get at lists of the keys and values with `keys()` and `values()`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Hashes have no particular internal order, though you can sort the keys and loop through them.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Just like special scalars and arrays, there are also special hashes.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The most well known of these is `%ENV` which contains environment variables.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Read all about it (and other special variables) in perlvar.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Scalars, arrays and hashes are documented more fully in perldata.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Note that `$name`, `@name`, and `%name` are three different variables.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] It can be confusing to use the same alphanumerics to represent different variables, but in some situations it might be clarifying; one such could be to use `$name` to represent the particular element currently of interest within the array `@name`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The naming choice is yours; the Perl interpreter doesn't care.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] When multiple variables have the same name, using square brackets versus curly braces tells the interpreter which one is meant.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] More complex data types can be constructed using references, which allow you to build lists and hashes within lists and hashes.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] A reference is a scalar value and can refer to any other Perl data type.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] So by storing a reference as the value of an array or hash element, you can easily create lists and hashes within lists and hashes.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The following example shows a 2 level hash of hash structure using anonymous hash references.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Exhaustive information on the topic of references can be found in perlreftut, perllol, perlref and perldsc.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] However, the above usage will create global variables throughout your program, which is bad programming practice.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] `my` creates lexically scoped variables instead.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The variables are scoped to the block (i.e. a bunch of statements surrounded by curly-braces) in which they are defined.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Using `my` in combination with a `use strict;` at the top of your Perl scripts means that the interpreter will pick up certain common programming errors.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] For instance, in the example above, the final `print $y` would cause a compile-time error and prevent you from running the program.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Perl has most of the usual conditional and looping constructs.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The conditions can be any Perl expression.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] See the list of operators in the next section for information on comparison and boolean logic operators, which are commonly used in conditional statements.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] This is provided as a more readable version of `if (!*condition*)`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Note that the braces are required in Perl, even if you've only got one line in the block.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The C style for loop is rarely needed in Perl since Perl provides the more friendly list scanning `foreach` loop.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The `foreach` keyword is actually a synonym for the `for` keyword.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] For more detail on looping constructs (and some that weren't mentioned in this overview) see perlsyn.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Perl comes with a wide selection of builtin functions.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Some of the ones we've already seen include `print`, `sort` and `reverse`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] A list of them is given at the start of perlfunc and you can easily read about any given function by using `perldoc -f *functionname*`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] (Why do we have separate numeric and string comparisons?
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Because we don't have special variable types, and Perl needs to know whether to sort numerically (where 99 is less than 100) or alphabetically (where 100 comes before 99).
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] (`and`, `or` and `not` aren't just in the above table as descriptions of the operators.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] They're also supported as operators in their own right.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] They're more readable than the C-style operators, but have different precedence to `&&` and friends.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You can open a file for input or output using the `open()` function.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You can read from an open filehandle using the `<>` operator.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Reading in the whole file at one time is called slurping.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] It can be useful but it may be a memory hog.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Most text file processing can be done a line at a time with Perl's looping constructs.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] We've already seen how to print to standard output using `print()`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Perl's regular expression support is both broad and deep, and is the subject of lengthy documentation in perlrequick, perlretut, and elsewhere.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The `//` matching operator is documented in perlop.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] It operates on `$_` by default, or can be bound to another variable using the `=~` binding operator (also documented in perlop).
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The `s///` substitution operator is documented in perlop.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You don't just have to match on fixed strings.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] In fact, you can match on just about anything you could dream of by using more complex regular expressions.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Note that in the above, `$` doesn't match a dollar sign.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] In contrast, the characters `a`, `e`, `i`, `o`, and `u`, for example, are not metacharacters.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Metacharacters normally match something that isn't their literal value.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] There are a few more metacharacters than the ones above.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Some quantifier ones are given below, and the full list is in "Metacharacters" in perlre.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] To make a metacharacter match its literal value, you "escape" (or "quote") it, by preceding it with a backslash.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Hence, `\$` does match a dollar sign, and `\\` matches a literal backslash.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Note also that above, the string `\s`, for example, doesn't match a backslash followed by the letter `s`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] In this case, preceding the non-metacharacter `s` with a backslash turns it into something that doesn't match its literal value.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Such a sequence is called an "escape sequence". perlrebackslash documents all of the current ones.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] A warning is raised if you escape a character that isn't a metacharacter and isn't part of a currently defined escape sequence.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] You can specify how many of the previous thing you want to match on by using quantifiers (where "thing" means one of: a literal character, one of the constructs listed above, or a group of either of them in parentheses).
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] As well as grouping, parentheses serve a second purpose.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] They can be used to capture the results of parts of the regexp match for later use.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The results end up in `$1`, `$2` and so on.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Perl regexps also support backreferences, lookaheads, and all kinds of other complex details.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Read all about them in perlrequick, perlretut, and perlre.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Well, the arguments to a subroutine are available to us as a special array called `@_` (see perlvar for more on that).
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] The default argument to the `shift` function just happens to be `@_`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] So `my $logmessage = shift;` shifts the first item off the list of arguments and assigns it to `$logmessage`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] For more information on writing subroutines, see perlsub.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] OO Perl is relatively simple and is implemented using references which know what sort of object they are based on Perl's concept of packages.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] However, OO Perl is largely beyond the scope of this document.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] As a beginning Perl programmer, your most common use of OO Perl will be in using third-party modules, which are documented below.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Perl modules provide a range of features to help you avoid reinventing the wheel, and can be downloaded from CPAN.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] A number of popular modules are included with the Perl distribution itself.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Categories of modules range from text manipulation to network protocols to database integration to graphics.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] A categorized list of modules is also available from CPAN.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] To learn how to install modules you download from CPAN, read perlmodinstall.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] To learn how to use a particular module, use `perldoc *Module::Name*`.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] Typically you will want to `use *Module::Name*`, which will then give you access to exported functions or an OO interface to the module.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] perlfaq contains questions and answers related to many common tasks, and often provides suggestions for good CPAN modules to use.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] perlmod describes Perl modules in general. perlmodlib lists the modules which came with your Perl installation.
[src:perl-docs/perlintro] If you feel the urge to write Perl modules, perlnewmod will give you good advice.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This page describes the syntax of regular expressions in Perl.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] If you haven't used regular expressions before, a tutorial introduction is available in perlretut.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] If you know just a little about them, a quick-start introduction is available in perlrequick.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Except for "The Basics" section, this page assumes you are familiar with regular expression basics, like what is a "pattern", what does it look like, and how it is basically used.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For a reference on how they are used, plus various examples of the same, see discussions of `m//`, `s///`, `qr//` and `"??"` in "Regexp Quote-Like Operators" in perlop.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] New in v5.22, `use re 'strict'` applies stricter rules than otherwise when compiling regular expression patterns.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] It can find things that, while legal, may not be what you intended.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Regular expressions are strings with the very particular syntax and meaning described in this document and auxiliary documents referred to by this one.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Patterns are used to determine if some other string, called the "target", has (or doesn't have) the characteristics specified by the pattern.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] We call this "matching" the target string against the pattern.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This evaluates to true if and only if the string in the variable `$foo` contains somewhere in it, the sequence of characters "a", "b", then "c".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Patterns that aren't already stored in some variable must be delimited, at both ends, by delimiter characters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] These are often, as in the example above, forward slashes, and the typical way a pattern is written in documentation is with those slashes.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] If the pattern contains its delimiter within it, that delimiter must be escaped.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Prefixing it with a backslash (*e.g.*, `"/foo\/bar/"`) serves this purpose.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Any single character in a pattern matches that same character in the target string, unless the character is a *metacharacter* with a special meaning described in this document.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] A sequence of non-metacharacters matches the same sequence in the target string, as we saw above with `m/abc/`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Only a few characters (all of them being ASCII punctuation characters) are metacharacters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The most commonly used one is a dot `"."`, which normally matches almost any character (including a dot itself).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] You can cause characters that normally function as metacharacters to be interpreted literally by prefixing them with a `"\"`, just like the pattern's delimiter must be escaped if it also occurs within the pattern.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Thus, `"\."` matches just a literal dot, `"."` instead of its normal meaning.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This means that the backslash is also a metacharacter, so `"\\"` matches a single `"\"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] And a sequence that contains an escaped metacharacter matches the same sequence (but without the escape) in the target string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] So, the pattern `/blur\\fl/` would match any target string that contains the sequence `"blur\fl"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The metacharacter `"|"` is used to match one thing or another.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] is TRUE if and only if `$foo` contains either the sequence `"this"` or the sequence `"that"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Like all metacharacters, prefixing the `"|"` with a backslash makes it match the plain punctuation character; in its case, the VERTICAL LINE.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] is TRUE if and only if `$foo` contains the sequence `"this|that"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] You aren't limited to just a single `"|"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] is TRUE if and only if `$foo` contains any of those 4 sequences from the children's story "Jack and the Beanstalk".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] As you can see, the `"|"` binds less tightly than a sequence of ordinary characters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] We can override this by using the grouping metacharacters, the parentheses `"("` and `")"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] is TRUE if and only if `$foo` contains either the sequence `"this thing"` or the sequence `"that thing"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The portions of the string that match the portions of the pattern enclosed in parentheses are normally made available separately for use later in the pattern, substitution, or program.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This is called "capturing", and it can get complicated.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The first alternative includes everything from the last pattern delimiter (`"("`, `"(?:"` (described later), *etc*. or the beginning of the pattern) up to the first `"|"`, and the last alternative contains everything from the last `"|"` to the next closing pattern delimiter.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] That's why it's common practice to include alternatives in parentheses: to minimize confusion about where they start and end.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Alternatives are tried from left to right, so the first alternative found for which the entire expression matches, is the one that is chosen.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This means that alternatives are not necessarily greedy.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For example: when matching `foo|foot` against `"barefoot"`, only the `"foo"` part will match, as that is the first alternative tried, and it successfully matches the target string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Besides taking away the special meaning of a metacharacter, a prefixed backslash changes some letter and digit characters away from matching just themselves to instead have special meaning.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] These are called "escape sequences", and all such are described in perlrebackslash.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] A backslash sequence (of a letter or digit) that doesn't currently have special meaning to Perl will raise a warning if warnings are enabled, as those are reserved for potential future use.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] One such sequence is `\b`, which matches a boundary of some sort.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `\b{wb}` and a few others give specialized types of boundaries.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] (They are all described in detail starting at "\b{}, \b, \B{}, \B" in perlrebackslash.) Note that these don't match characters, but the zero-width spaces between characters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] They are an example of a zero-width assertion.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] It evaluates to TRUE if, besides those 4 words, any of the sequences "feed", "field", "Defoe", "fume", and many others are in `$foo`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The final example shows that the characters `"{"` and `"}"` are metacharacters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Another use for escape sequences is to specify characters that cannot (or which you prefer not to) be written literally.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] These are described in detail in "Character Escapes" in perlrebackslash, but the next three paragraphs briefly describe some of them.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Various control characters can be written in C language style: `"\n"` matches a newline, `"\t"` a tab, `"\r"` a carriage return, `"\f"` a form feed, *etc*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] More generally, `\*nnn*`, where *nnn* is a string of three octal digits, matches the character whose native code point is *nnn*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] You can easily run into trouble if you don't have exactly three digits.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] So always use three, or since Perl 5.14, you can use `\o{...}` to specify any number of octal digits.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Similarly, `\x*nn*`, where *nn* are hexadecimal digits, matches the character whose native ordinal is *nn*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Again, not using exactly two digits is a recipe for disaster, but you can use `\x{...}` to specify any number of hex digits.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Besides being a metacharacter, the `"."` is an example of a "character class", something that can match any single character of a given set of them.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] In its case, the set is just about all possible characters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Perl predefines several character classes besides the `"."`; there is a separate reference page about just these, perlrecharclass.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] You can define your own custom character classes, by putting into your pattern in the appropriate place(s), a list of all the characters you want in the set.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] You do this by enclosing the list within `[]` bracket characters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] These are called "bracketed character classes" when we are being precise, but often the word "bracketed" is dropped.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] (Dropping it usually doesn't cause confusion.) This means that the `"["` character is another metacharacter.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] It doesn't match anything just by itself; it is used only to tell Perl that what follows it is a bracketed character class.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] If you want to match a literal left square bracket, you must escape it, like `"\["`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The matching `"]"` is also a metacharacter; again it doesn't match anything by itself, but just marks the end of your custom class to Perl.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] It is an example of a "sometimes metacharacter".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The list of characters within the character class gives the set of characters matched by the class.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] But if the first character after the `"["` is `"^"`, the class instead matches any character not in the list.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Within a list, the `"-"` character specifies a range of characters, so that `a-z` represents all characters between "a" and "z", inclusive.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] If you want either `"-"` or `"]"` itself to be a member of a class, put it at the start of the list (possibly after a `"^"`), or escape it with a backslash.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `"-"` is also taken literally when it is at the end of the list, just before the closing `"]"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] (The following all specify the same class of three characters: `[-az]`, `[az-]`, and `[a\-z]`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] There is lots more to bracketed character classes; full details are in "Bracketed Character Classes" in perlrecharclass.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] "The Basics" introduced some of the metacharacters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Most of them have the same meaning as in the *egrep* command.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Only the `"\"` is always a metacharacter.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The others are metacharacters just sometimes.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The following tables lists all of them, summarizes their use, and gives the contexts where they are metacharacters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Outside those contexts or if prefixed by a `"\"`, they match their corresponding punctuation character.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] In some cases, their meaning varies depending on various pattern modifiers that alter the default behaviors.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Notice that most of the metacharacters lose their special meaning when they occur in a bracketed character class, except `"^"` has a different meaning when it is at the beginning of such a class.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] And `"-"` and `"]"` are metacharacters only at restricted positions within bracketed character classes; while `"}"` is a metacharacter only when closing a special construct started by `"{"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] In double-quotish context, as is usually the case, you need to be careful about `"$"` and the non-metacharacter `"@"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Those could interpolate variables, which may or may not be what you intended.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] These rules were designed for compactness of expression, rather than legibility and maintainability.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The "/x and /xx" pattern modifiers allow you to insert white space to improve readability.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] And use of `re 'strict'` adds extra checking to catch some typos that might silently compile into something unintended.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] By default, the `"^"` character is guaranteed to match only the beginning of the string, the `"$"` character only the end (or before the newline at the end), and Perl does certain optimizations with the assumption that the string contains only one line.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Embedded newlines will not be matched by `"^"` or `"$"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] You may, however, wish to treat a string as a multi-line buffer, such that the `"^"` will match after any newline within the string (except if the newline is the last character in the string), and `"$"` will match before any newline.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] At the cost of a little more overhead, you can do this by using the `"/m"` modifier on the pattern match operator.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] To simplify multi-line substitutions, the `"."` character never matches a newline unless you use the `/s` modifier, which in effect tells Perl to pretend the string is a single line--even if it isn't.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The default behavior for matching can be changed, using various modifiers.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Modifiers that relate to the interpretation of the pattern are listed just below.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Modifiers that alter the way a pattern is used by Perl are detailed in "Regexp Quote-Like Operators" in perlop and "Gory details of parsing quoted constructs" in perlop.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Modifiers can be added dynamically; see "Extended Patterns" below.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Treat the string being matched against as multiple lines.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] That is, change `"^"` and `"$"` from matching the start of the string's first line and the end of its last line to matching the start and end of each line within the string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] That is, change `"."` to match any character whatsoever, even a newline, which normally it would not match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Used together, as `/ms`, they let the `"."` match any character whatsoever, while still allowing `"^"` and `"$"` to match, respectively, just after and just before newlines within the string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For example, "A" will match "a" under `/i`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] If locale matching rules are in effect, the case map is taken from the current locale for code points less than 255, and from Unicode rules for larger code points.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] However, matches that would cross the Unicode rules/non-Unicode rules boundary (ords 255/256) will not succeed, unless the locale is a UTF-8 one.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] There are a number of Unicode characters that match a sequence of multiple characters under `/i`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For example, `LATIN SMALL LIGATURE FI` should match the sequence `fi`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Perl is not currently able to do this when the multiple characters are in the pattern and are split between groupings, or when one or more are quantified.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Perl doesn't match multiple characters in a bracketed character class unless the character that maps to them is explicitly mentioned, and it doesn't match them at all if the character class is inverted, which otherwise could be highly confusing.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] See "Bracketed Character Classes" in perlrecharclass, and "Negation" in perlrecharclass.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Extend your pattern's legibility by permitting whitespace and comments.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Preserve the string matched such that `${^PREMATCH}`, `${^MATCH}`, and `${^POSTMATCH}` are available for use after matching.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] In Perl 5.20 and higher this is ignored.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Due to a new copy-on-write mechanism, `${^PREMATCH}`, `${^MATCH}`, and `${^POSTMATCH}` will be available after the match regardless of the modifier.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] These modifiers, all new in 5.14, affect which character-set rules (Unicode, *etc*.) are used, as described below in "Character set modifiers".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Prevent the grouping metacharacters `()` from capturing.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This modifier, new in 5.22, will stop `$1`, `$2`, *etc*... from being filled in.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `/n` can be negated on a per-group basis.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Alternatively, named captures may still be used.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] There are a number of flags that can be found at the end of regular expression constructs that are *not* generic regular expression flags, but apply to the operation being performed, like matching or substitution (`m//` or `s///` respectively).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Regular expression modifiers are usually written in documentation as *e.g.*, "the `/x` modifier", even though the delimiter in question might not really be a slash.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The modifiers `/imnsxadlup` may also be embedded within the regular expression itself using the `(?...)` construct, see "Extended Patterns" below.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Some of the modifiers require more explanation than given in the "Overview" above.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] A single `/x` tells the regular expression parser to ignore most whitespace that is neither backslashed nor within a bracketed character class, nor within the characters of a multi-character metapattern like `(?i: ... )`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] You can use this to break up your regular expression into more readable parts.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Also, the `"#"` character is treated as a metacharacter introducing a comment that runs up to the pattern's closing delimiter, or to the end of the current line if the pattern extends onto the next line.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Hence, this is very much like an ordinary Perl code comment.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Use of `/x` means that if you want real whitespace or `"#"` characters in the pattern (outside a bracketed character class, which is unaffected by `/x`), then you'll either have to escape them (using backslashes or `\Q...\E`) or encode them using octal, hex, or `\N{}` or `\p{name=...}` escapes.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] It is ineffective to try to continue a comment onto the next line by escaping the `\n` with a backslash or `\Q`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] You can use "(?#text)" to create a comment that ends earlier than the end of the current line, but `text` also can't contain the closing delimiter unless escaped with a backslash.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] A common pitfall is to forget that `"#"` characters (outside a bracketed character class) begin a comment under `/x` and are not matched literally.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Just keep that in mind when trying to puzzle out why a particular `/x` pattern isn't working as expected.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Inside a bracketed character class, `"#"` retains its non-special, literal meaning.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Starting in Perl v5.26, if the modifier has a second `"x"` within it, the effect of a single `/x` is increased.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Note that this unfortunately doesn't mean that your bracketed classes can contain comments or extend over multiple lines.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] A `#` inside a character class is still just a literal `#`, and doesn't introduce a comment.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] And, unless the closing bracket is on the same line as the opening one, the newline character (and everything on the next line(s) until terminated by a `]` will be part of the class, just as if you'd written `\n`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Taken together, these features go a long way towards making Perl's regular expressions more readable.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Note that anything inside a `\Q...\E` stays unaffected by `/x`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] And note that `/x` doesn't affect space interpretation within a single multi-character construct.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Within any delimiters for such a construct, allowed spaces are not affected by `/x`, and depend on the construct.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For example, all constructs using curly braces as delimiters, such as `\x{...}` can have blanks within but adjacent to the braces, but not elsewhere, and no non-blank space characters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] An exception are Unicode properties which follow Unicode rules, for which see "Properties accessible through \p{} and \P{}" in perluniprops.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `/d`, `/u`, `/a`, and `/l`, available starting in 5.14, are called the character set modifiers; they affect the character set rules used for the regular expression.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The `/d`, `/u`, and `/l` modifiers are not likely to be of much use to you, and so you need not worry about them very much.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] They exist for Perl's internal use, so that complex regular expression data structures can be automatically serialized and later exactly reconstituted, including all their nuances.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] But, since Perl can't keep a secret, and there may be rare instances where they are useful, they are documented here.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The `/a` modifier, on the other hand, may be useful.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Its purpose is to allow code that is to work mostly on ASCII data to not have to concern itself with Unicode.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Briefly, `/l` sets the character set to that of whatever **L**ocale is in effect at the time of the execution of the pattern match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `/u` sets the character set to **U**nicode.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `/a` also sets the character set to Unicode, BUT adds several restrictions for **A**SCII-safe matching.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `/d` is the old, problematic, pre-5.14 **D**efault character set behavior.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Its only use is to force that old behavior.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] At any given time, exactly one of these modifiers is in effect.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Their existence allows Perl to keep the originally compiled behavior of a regular expression, regardless of what rules are in effect when it is actually executed.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] And if it is interpolated into a larger regex, the original's rules continue to apply to it, and don't affect the other parts.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The `/l` and `/u` modifiers are automatically selected for regular expressions compiled within the scope of various pragmas, and we recommend that in general, you use those pragmas instead of specifying these modifiers explicitly.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For one thing, the modifiers affect only pattern matching, and do not extend to even any replacement done, whereas using the pragmas gives consistent results for all appropriate operations within their scopes.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] will match "foo" using the locale's rules for case-insensitive matching, but the `/l` does not affect how the `\U` operates.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Most likely you want both of them to use locale rules.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] To do this, instead compile the regular expression within the scope of `use locale`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This both implicitly adds the `/l`, and applies locale rules to the `\U`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The lesson is to `use locale`, and not `/l` explicitly.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] to get Unicode rules, as the `\L` in the former (but not necessarily the latter) would also use Unicode rules.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] More detail on each of the modifiers follows.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Most likely you don't need to know this detail for `/l`, `/u`, and `/d`, and can skip ahead to /a.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] means to use the current locale's rules (see perllocale) when pattern matching.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For example, `\w` will match the "word" characters of that locale, and `"/i"` case-insensitive matching will match according to the locale's case folding rules.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The locale used will be the one in effect at the time of execution of the pattern match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This may not be the same as the compilation-time locale, and can differ from one match to another if there is an intervening call of the setlocale() function.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Prior to v5.20, Perl did not support multi-byte locales.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Starting then, UTF-8 locales are supported.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] No other multi byte locales are ever likely to be supported.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] However, in all locales, one can have code points above 255 and these will always be treated as Unicode no matter what locale is in effect.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Under Unicode rules, there are a few case-insensitive matches that cross the 255/256 boundary.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Except for UTF-8 locales in Perls v5.20 and later, these are disallowed under `/l`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] In a UTF-8 locale in v5.20 and later, the only visible difference between locale and non-locale in regular expressions should be tainting, if your perl supports taint checking (see perlsec).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This modifier may be specified to be the default by `use locale`, but see "Which character set modifier is in effect?".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] means to use Unicode rules when pattern matching.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] On ASCII platforms, this means that the code points between 128 and 255 take on their Latin-1 (ISO-8859-1) meanings (which are the same as Unicode's).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] (Otherwise Perl considers their meanings to be undefined.) Thus, under this modifier, the ASCII platform effectively becomes a Unicode platform; and hence, for example, `\w` will match any of the more than 100_000 word characters in Unicode.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Unlike most locales, which are specific to a language and country pair, Unicode classifies all the characters that are letters *somewhere* in the world as `\w`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For example, your locale might not think that `LATIN SMALL LETTER ETH` is a letter (unless you happen to speak Icelandic), but Unicode does.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Similarly, all the characters that are decimal digits somewhere in the world will match `\d`; this is hundreds, not 10, possible matches.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] And some of those digits look like some of the 10 ASCII digits, but mean a different number, so a human could easily think a number is a different quantity than it really is.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] For example, `BENGALI DIGIT FOUR` (U+09EA) looks very much like an `ASCII DIGIT EIGHT` (U+0038), and `LEPCHA DIGIT SIX` (U+1C46) looks very much like an `ASCII DIGIT FIVE` (U+0035).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] And, `\d+`, may match strings of digits that are a mixture from different writing systems, creating a security issue.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] A fraudulent website, for example, could display the price of something using U+1C46, and it would appear to the user that something cost 500 units, but it really costs 600.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] A browser that enforced script runs ("Script Runs") would prevent that fraudulent display.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] "num()" in Unicode::UCD can also be used to sort this out.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Or the `/a` modifier can be used to force `\d` to match just the ASCII 0 through 9.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Also, under this modifier, case-insensitive matching works on the full set of Unicode characters.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The `KELVIN SIGN`, for example matches the letters "k" and "K"; and `LATIN SMALL LIGATURE FF` matches the sequence "ff", which, if you're not prepared, might make it look like a hexadecimal constant, presenting another potential security issue.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] See https://unicode.org/reports/tr36 for a detailed discussion of Unicode security issues.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This modifier may be specified to be the default by `use feature 'unicode_strings`, `use locale ':not_characters'`, or `use v5.12` (or higher), but see "Which character set modifier is in effect?".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Regarding the "UTF8 flag" references above: normally Perl applications shouldn't think about that flag.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] It's part of Perl's internals, so it can change whenever Perl wants.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `/d` may thus cause unpredictable results.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This bug has become rather infamous, leading to yet other (without swearing) names for this modifier like "Dicey" and "Dodgy".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Under Perl's default configuration this modifier is automatically selected by default when none of the others are, so yet another name for it (unfortunately) is "Default".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Whenever you can, use the `unicode_strings` to cause `/u` to be the default instead.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This modifier stands for ASCII-restrict (or ASCII-safe).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This modifier may be doubled-up to increase its effect.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] When it appears singly, it causes the sequences `\d`, `\s`, `\w`, and the Posix character classes to match only in the ASCII range.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] They thus revert to their pre-5.6, pre-Unicode meanings.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This modifier is useful for people who only incidentally use Unicode, and who do not wish to be burdened with its complexities and security concerns.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] With `/a`, one can write `\d` with confidence that it will only match ASCII characters, and should the need arise to match beyond ASCII, you can instead use `\p{Digit}` (or `\p{Word}` for `\w`).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] There are similar `\p{...}` constructs that can match beyond ASCII both white space (see "Whitespace" in perlrecharclass), and Posix classes (see "POSIX Character Classes" in perlrecharclass).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Thus, this modifier doesn't mean you can't use Unicode, it means that to get Unicode matching you must explicitly use a construct (`\p{}`, `\P{}`) that signals Unicode.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] As you would expect, this modifier causes, for example, `\D` to mean the same thing as `[^0-9]`; in fact, all non-ASCII characters match `\D`, `\S`, and `\W`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `\b` still means to match at the boundary between `\w` and `\W`, using the `/a` definitions of them (similarly for `\B`).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Otherwise, `/a` behaves like the `/u` modifier, in that case-insensitive matching uses Unicode rules; for example, "k" will match the Unicode `\N{KELVIN SIGN}` under `/i` matching, and code points in the Latin1 range, above ASCII will have Unicode rules when it comes to case-insensitive matching.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] To forbid ASCII/non-ASCII matches (like "k" with `\N{KELVIN SIGN}`), specify the `"a"` twice, for example `/aai` or `/aia`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] To summarize, this modifier provides protection for applications that don't wish to be exposed to all of Unicode.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Specifying it twice gives added protection.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This modifier may be specified to be the default by `use re '/a'` or `use re '/aa'`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] If you do so, you may actually have occasion to use the `/u` modifier explicitly if there are a few regular expressions where you do want full Unicode rules (but even here, it's best if everything were under feature `"unicode_strings"`, along with the `use re '/aa'`).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Also see "Which character set modifier is in effect?".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Which of these modifiers is in effect at any given point in a regular expression depends on a fairly complex set of interactions.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] These have been designed so that in general you don't have to worry about it, but this section gives the gory details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] As explained below in "Extended Patterns" it is possible to explicitly specify modifiers that apply only to portions of a regular expression.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The innermost always has priority over any outer ones, and one applying to the whole expression has priority over any of the default settings that are described in the remainder of this section.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] The `use re '/foo'` pragma can be used to set default modifiers (including these) for regular expressions compiled within its scope.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] This pragma has precedence over the other pragmas listed below that also change the defaults.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Note that the /x modifier does NOT affect `split STR` patterns.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Otherwise, `use locale` sets the default modifier to `/l`; and `use feature 'unicode_strings`, or `use v5.12` (or higher) set the default to `/u` when not in the same scope as either `use locale` or `use bytes`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] If none of the above apply, for backwards compatibility reasons, the `/d` modifier is the one in effect by default.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] As this can lead to unexpected results, it is best to specify which other rule set should be used.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] Prior to 5.14, there were no explicit modifiers, but `/l` was implied for regexes compiled within the scope of `use locale`, and `/d` was implied otherwise.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] However, interpolating a regex into a larger regex would ignore the original compilation in favor of whatever was in effect at the time of the second compilation.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] There were a number of inconsistencies (bugs) with the `/d` modifier, where Unicode rules would be used when inappropriate, and vice versa.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p01] `\p{}` did not imply Unicode rules, and neither did all occurrences of `\N{}`, until 5.12.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Quantifiers are used when a particular portion of a pattern needs to match a certain number (or numbers) of times.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] If there isn't a quantifier the number of times to match is exactly one.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] (If a non-escaped curly bracket occurs in a context other than one of the quantifiers listed above, where it does not form part of a backslashed sequence like `\x{...}`, it is either a fatal syntax error, or treated as a regular character, generally with a deprecation warning raised.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] To escape it, you can precede it with a backslash (`"\{"`) or enclose it within square brackets (`"[{]"`).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] This change will allow for future syntax extensions (like making the lower bound of a quantifier optional), and better error checking of quantifiers).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] *n* and *m* are limited to non-negative integral values less than a preset limit defined when perl is built.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] This is usually 65534 on the most common platforms.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] By default, a quantified subpattern is "greedy", that is, it will match as many times as possible (given a particular starting location) while still allowing the rest of the pattern to match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] If you want it to match the minimum number of times possible, follow the quantifier with a `"?"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Normally when a quantified subpattern does not allow the rest of the overall pattern to match, Perl will backtrack.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] However, this behaviour is sometimes undesirable.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Thus Perl provides the "possessive" quantifier form as well.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] will never match, as the `a++` will gobble up all the `"a"`'s in the string and won't leave any for the remaining part of the pattern.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] This feature can be extremely useful to give perl hints about where it shouldn't backtrack.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] as we know that if the final quote does not match, backtracking will not help.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See the independent subexpression `"(?>*pattern*)"` for more details; possessive quantifiers are just syntactic sugar for that construct.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Note that the possessive quantifier modifier can not be combined with the non-greedy modifier.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Details are in "Quote and Quote-like Operators" in perlop.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "Bracketed Character Classes" in perlrecharclass for details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "POSIX Character Classes" in perlrecharclass for details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "Misc" in perlrebackslash for details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "Extended Patterns" below for details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] When of the form `\N{*NAME*}`, it matches the character or character sequence whose name is *NAME*; and similarly when of the form `\N{U+*hex*}`, it matches the character whose Unicode code point is *hex*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Otherwise it matches any character but `\n`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "Extended Bracketed Character Classes" in perlrecharclass for details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] A Unicode boundary (`\b{}`), available starting in v5.22, is a spot between two characters, or before the first character in the string, or after the final character in the string where certain criteria defined by Unicode are met.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "\b{}, \b, \B{}, \B" in perlrebackslash for details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] A word boundary (`\b`) is a spot between two characters that has a `\w` on one side of it and a `\W` on the other side of it (in either order), counting the imaginary characters off the beginning and end of the string as matching a `\W`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] To match the actual end of the string and not ignore an optional trailing newline, use `\z`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] The `\G` assertion can be used to chain global matches (using `m//g`), as described in "Regexp Quote-Like Operators" in perlop.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] It is also useful when writing `lex`-like scanners, when you have several patterns that you want to match against consequent substrings of your string; see the previous reference.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] The actual location where `\G` will match can also be influenced by using `pos()` as an lvalue: see "pos" in perlfunc.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Note that the rule for zero-length matches (see "Repeated Patterns Matching a Zero-length Substring") is modified somewhat, in that contents to the left of `\G` are not counted when determining the length of the match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] It will print 'A' and then terminate, as it considers the match to be zero-width, and thus will not match at the same position twice in a row.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] It is worth noting that `\G` improperly used can result in an infinite loop.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Take care when using patterns that include `\G` in an alternation.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] The grouping construct `( ... )` creates capture groups (also referred to as capture buffers).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] To refer to the current contents of a group later on, within the same pattern, use `\g1` (or `\g{1}`) for the first, `\g2` (or `\g{2}`) for the second, and so on.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] There is no limit to the number of captured substrings that you may use.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Groups are numbered with the leftmost open parenthesis being number 1, *etc*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] If a group did not match, the associated backreference won't match either.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] (This can happen if the group is optional, or in a different branch of an alternation.) You can omit the `"g"`, and write `"\1"`, *etc*, but there are some issues with this form, described below.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] You can also refer to capture groups relatively, by using a negative number, so that `\g-1` and `\g{-1}` both refer to the immediately preceding capture group, and `\g-2` and `\g{-2}` both refer to the group before it.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] This allows you to interpolate regexes into larger regexes and not have to worry about the capture groups being renumbered.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] You can dispense with numbers altogether and create named capture groups.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] The notation is `(?<*name*>...)` to declare and `\g{*name*}` to reference.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] (To be compatible with .Net regular expressions, `\g{*name*}` may also be written as `\k{*name*}`, `\k<*name*>` or `\k'*name*'`.) *name* must not begin with a number, nor contain hyphens.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] When different groups within the same pattern have the same name, any reference to that name assumes the leftmost defined group.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Named groups count in absolute and relative numbering, and so can also be referred to by those numbers.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Capture group contents are dynamically scoped and available to you outside the pattern until the end of the enclosing block or until the next successful match in the same scope, whichever comes first.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "Compound Statements" in perlsyn and "Scoping Rules of Regex Variables" in perlvar for more details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] You can access the contents of a capture group by absolute number (using `"$1"` instead of `"\g1"`, *etc*); or by name via the `%+` hash, using `"$+{*name*}"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Braces are required in referring to named capture groups, but are optional for absolute or relative numbered ones.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Braces are safer when creating a regex by concatenating smaller strings.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] For example if you have `qr/$x$y/`, and `$x` contained `"\g1"`, and `$y` contained `"37"`, you would get `/\g137/` which is probably not what you intended.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] If you use braces, you may also optionally add any number of blank (space or tab) characters within but adjacent to the braces, like `\g{ -1 }`, or `\k{ *name* }`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] The `\g` and `\k` notations were introduced in Perl 5.10.0.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Prior to that there were no named nor relative numbered capture groups.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Absolute numbered groups were referred to using `\1`, `\2`, *etc*., and this notation is still accepted (and likely always will be).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] But it leads to some ambiguities if there are more than 9 capture groups, as `\10` could mean either the tenth capture group, or the character whose ordinal in octal is 010 (a backspace in ASCII).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Perl resolves this ambiguity by interpreting `\10` as a backreference only if at least 10 left parentheses have opened before it.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Likewise `\11` is a backreference only if at least 11 left parentheses have opened before it.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] `\1` through `\9` are always interpreted as backreferences.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] There are several examples below that illustrate these perils.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] You can avoid the ambiguity by always using `\g{}` or `\g` if you mean capturing groups; and for octal constants always using `\o{}`, or for `\077` and below, using 3 digits padded with leading zeros, since a leading zero implies an octal constant.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] The `\*digit*` notation also works in certain circumstances outside the pattern.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "Warning on \1 Instead of $1" below for details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Several special variables also refer back to portions of the previous match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] `$+` returns whatever the last bracket match matched.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] (At one point `$0` did also, but now it returns the name of the program.) $` returns everything before the matched string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] `$'` returns everything after the matched string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] And `$^N` contains whatever was matched by the most-recently closed group (submatch).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] `$^N` can be used in extended patterns (see below), for example to assign a submatch to a variable.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] These special variables, like the `%+` hash and the numbered match variables (`$1`, `$2`, `$3`, *etc*.) are dynamically scoped until the end of the enclosing block or until the next successful match, whichever comes first.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] The `@{^CAPTURE}` array may be used to access ALL of the capture buffers as an array without needing to know how many there are.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] will place a copy of each capture variable, `$1`, `$2` etc, into the `@captured` array.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] See "Demarcated variable names using braces" in perldata for more on this notation.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Perl uses the same mechanism to produce `$1`, `$2`, *etc*, so you also pay a price for each pattern that contains capturing parentheses.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] (To avoid this cost while retaining the grouping behaviour, use the extended regular expression `(?: ... )` instead.) But if you never use `$&`, $` or `$'`, then patterns *without* capturing parentheses will not be penalized.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] So avoid `$&`, `$'`, and $` if you can, but if you can't (and some algorithms really appreciate them), once you've used them once, use them at will, because you've already paid the price.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Perl 5.16 introduced a slightly more efficient mechanism that notes separately whether each of $`, `$&`, and `$'` have been seen, and thus may only need to copy part of the string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Perl 5.20 introduced a much more efficient copy-on-write mechanism which eliminates any slowdown.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] As another workaround for this problem, Perl 5.10.0 introduced `${^PREMATCH}`, `${^MATCH}` and `${^POSTMATCH}`, which are equivalent to $`, `$&` and `$'`, **except** that they are only guaranteed to be defined after a successful match that was executed with the `/p` (preserve) modifier.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] The use of these variables incurs no global performance penalty, unlike their punctuation character equivalents, however at the trade-off that you have to tell perl when you want to use them.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] To cause a metacharacter to match its literal self, you precede it with a backslash.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Unlike some other regular expression languages, any sequence consisting of a backslash followed by a non-alphanumeric matches that non-alphanumeric, literally.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] So things like `\\`, `\(`, `\)`, `\[`, `\]`, `\{`, or `\}` are always interpreted as the literal character that follows the backslash.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] (That's not true when an alphanumeric character is preceded by a backslash.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] There are a few such "escape sequences", like `\w`, which have special matching behaviors in Perl.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] This changes `$pattern` so that the metacharacters are quoted.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] and be assured that any metacharacters in `$pattern` will match their literal selves.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] you don't have to have a separate `$pattern` variable.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] Beware that if you put literal backslashes (those not inside interpolated variables) between `\Q` and `\E`, double-quotish backslash interpolation may lead to confusing results.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] If you *need* to use literal backslashes within `\Q...\E`, consult "Gory details of parsing quoted constructs" in perlop.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] This simply adds backslashes before all non-"word" characters to disable any special meanings they might have.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] (If `use locale` is in effect, the current locale can affect the results.) This paradigm is inadequate for Unicode.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p02] `quotemeta()` and `\Q` are more fully described in "quotemeta" in perlfunc.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Perl also defines a consistent extension syntax for features not found in standard tools like **awk** and **lex**.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] The syntax for most of these is a pair of parentheses with a question mark as the first thing within the parentheses.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] The character after the question mark indicates the extension.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] A question mark was chosen for this and for the minimal-matching construct because 1) question marks are rare in older regular expressions, and 2) whenever you see one, you should stop and "question" exactly what is going on.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Note that Perl closes the comment as soon as it sees a `")"`, so there is no way to put a literal `")"` in the comment.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] The pattern's closing delimiter must be escaped by a backslash if it appears in the comment.
