[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] A fundamental feature of regular expression matching involves the notion called *backtracking*, which is currently used (when needed) by all regular non-possessive expression quantifiers, namely `"*"`, `*?`, `"+"`, `+?`, `{n,m}`, and `{n,m}?`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Backtracking is often optimized internally, but the general principle outlined here is valid.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] For a regular expression to match, the *entire* regular expression must match, not just part of it.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] So if the beginning of a pattern containing a quantifier succeeds in a way that causes later parts in the pattern to fail, the matching engine backs up and recalculates the beginning part--that's why it's called backtracking.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] When the match runs, the first part of the regular expression (`\b(foo)`) finds a possible match right at the beginning of the string, and loads up `$1` with "Foo".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] However, as soon as the matching engine sees that there's no whitespace following the "Foo" that it had saved in `$1`, it realizes its mistake and starts over again one character after where it had the tentative match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] This time it goes all the way until the next occurrence of "foo".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Sometimes minimal matching can help a lot.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Imagine you'd like to match everything between "foo" and "bar".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] That's because `.*` was greedy, so you get everything between the *first* "foo" and the *last* "bar".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Here it's more effective to use minimal matching to make sure you get the text between a "foo" and the first "bar" thereafter.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Let's say you'd like to match a number at the end of a string, and you also want to keep the preceding part of the match.
