[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] It's important to realize that a regular expression is merely a set of assertions that gives a definition of success.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] There may be 0, 1, or several different ways that the definition might succeed against a particular string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] And if there are multiple ways it might succeed, you need to understand backtracking to know which variety of success you will achieve.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] When using lookahead assertions and negations, this can all get even trickier.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Imagine you'd like to find a sequence of non-digits not followed by "123".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] But that isn't going to match; at least, not the way you're hoping.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] It claims that there is no 123 in the string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] You might have expected test 3 to fail because it seems to a more general purpose version of test 1.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] The important difference between them is that test 3 contains a quantifier (`\D*`) and so can use backtracking, whereas test 1 will not.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] What's happening is that you've asked "Is it true that at the start of `$x`, following 0 or more non-digits, you have something that's not 123?" If the pattern matcher had let `\D*` expand to "ABC", this would have caused the whole pattern to fail.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] The search engine will initially match `\D*` with "ABC".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Then it will try to match `(?!123)` with "123", which fails.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] But because a quantifier (`\D*`) has been used in the regular expression, the search engine can backtrack and retry the match differently in the hope of matching the complete regular expression.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] The pattern really, *really* wants to succeed, so it uses the standard pattern back-off-and-retry and lets `\D*` expand to just "AB" this time.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Now there's indeed something following "AB" that is not "123".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] We can deal with this by using both an assertion and a negation.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] We'll say that the first part in `$1` must be followed both by a digit and by something that's not "123".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] Remember that the lookaheads are zero-width expressions--they only look, but don't consume any of the string in their match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] In other words, the two zero-width assertions next to each other work as though they're ANDed together, just as you'd use any built-in assertions: `/^$/` matches only if you're at the beginning of the line AND the end of the line simultaneously.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] The deeper underlying truth is that juxtaposition in regular expressions always means AND, except when you write an explicit OR using the vertical bar.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p03] `/ab/` means match "a" AND (then) match "b", although the attempted matches are made at different positions because "a" is not a zero-width assertion, but a one-width assertion.
