[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] A script run is basically a sequence of characters, all from the same Unicode script (see "Scripts" in perlunicode), such as Latin or Greek.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] In most places a single word would never be written in multiple scripts, unless it is a spoofing attack.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Those letters could all be Latin (as in the example just above), or they could be all Cyrillic (except for the dot), or they could be a mixture of the two.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] In the case of an internet address the `.com` would be in Latin, And any Cyrillic ones would cause it to be a mixture, not a script run.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Someone clicking on such a link would not be directed to the real PayPal website, but an attacker would craft a look-alike one to attempt to gather sensitive information from the person.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Starting in Perl 5.28, it is now easy to detect strings that aren't script runs.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] What happens is that after *pattern* succeeds in matching, it is subjected to the additional criterion that every character in it must be from the same script (see exceptions below).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] If this isn't true, backtracking occurs until something all in the same script is found that matches, or all possibilities are exhausted.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This can cause a lot of backtracking, but generally, only malicious input will result in this, though the slow down could cause a denial of service attack.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] If your needs permit, it is best to make the pattern atomic to cut down on the amount of backtracking.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] In Taiwan, Japan, and Korea, it is common for text to have a mixture of characters from their native scripts and base Chinese.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Perl follows Unicode's UTS 39 (https://unicode.org/reports/tr39/) Unicode Security Mechanisms in allowing such mixtures.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] For example, the Japanese scripts Katakana and Hiragana are commonly mixed together in practice, along with some Chinese characters, and hence are treated as being in a single script run by Perl.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The rules used for matching decimal digits are slightly stricter.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Many scripts have their own sets of digits equivalent to the Western `0` through `9` ones.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] A few, such as Arabic, have more than one set.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] For a string to be considered a script run, all digits in it must come from the same set of ten, as determined by the first digit encountered.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] guarantees that the digits matched will all be from the same set of 10.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] You won't get a look-alike digit from a different script that has a different value than what it appears to be.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Unicode has three pseudo scripts that are handled specially.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] "Unknown" is applied to code points whose meaning has yet to be determined.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Perl currently will match as a script run, any single character string consisting of one of these code points.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] But any string longer than one code point containing one of these will not be considered a script run.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] "Inherited" is applied to characters that modify another, such as an accent of some type.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] These are considered to be in the script of the master character, and so never cause a script run to not match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This consists of mostly punctuation, emoji, characters used in mathematics and music, the ASCII digits `0` through `9`, and full-width forms of these digits.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] These characters can appear intermixed in text in many of the world's scripts.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] These also don't cause a script run to not match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] But like other scripts, all digits in a run must come from the same set of 10.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] You can add parentheses to *pattern* to capture, if desired.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] You will have to do this if you plan to use "(*ACCEPT) (*ACCEPT:arg)" and not have it bypass the script run checking.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The `Script_Extensions` property as modified by UTS 39 (https://unicode.org/reports/tr39/) is used as the basis for this feature.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] All characters in the sequence come from the Common script and/or the Inherited script and/or a single other script.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The script of a character is determined by the `Script_Extensions` property as modified by UTS 39 (https://unicode.org/reports/tr39/), as described above.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] All decimal digits in the sequence come from the same block of 10 consecutive digits.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] These special patterns are generally of the form `(**VERB*:*arg*)`.
