[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Any pattern containing a special backtracking verb that allows an argument has the special behaviour that when executed it sets the current package's `$REGERROR` and `$REGMARK` variables.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] On failure, the `$REGERROR` variable will be set to the *arg* value of the verb pattern, if the verb was involved in the failure of the match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] If the *arg* part of the pattern was omitted, then `$REGERROR` will be set to the name of the last `(*MARK:*NAME*)` pattern executed, or to TRUE if there was none.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Also, the `$REGMARK` variable will be set to FALSE.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] On a successful match, the `$REGERROR` variable will be set to FALSE, and the `$REGMARK` variable will be set to the name of the last `(*MARK:*NAME*)` pattern executed.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] See the explanation for the `(*MARK:*NAME*)` verb below for more details.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] If a pattern does not contain a special backtracking verb that allows an argument, then `$REGERROR` and `$REGMARK` are not touched at all.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This zero-width pattern prunes the backtracking tree at the current point when backtracked into on failure.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Consider the pattern `/*A* (*PRUNE) *B*/`, where *A* and *B* are complex patterns.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Until the `(*PRUNE)` verb is reached, *A* may backtrack as necessary to match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Once it is reached, matching continues in *B*, which may also backtrack as necessary; however, should B not match, then no further backtracking will take place, and the pattern will fail outright at the current starting position.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The following example counts all the possible matching strings in a pattern (without actually matching any of them).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Any number of `(*PRUNE)` assertions may be used in a pattern.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] See also `"(?>*pattern*)"` and possessive quantifiers for other ways to control backtracking.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] In some cases, the use of `(*PRUNE)` can be replaced with a `(?>pattern)` with no functional difference; however, `(*PRUNE)` can be used to handle cases that cannot be expressed using a `(?>pattern)` alone.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This zero-width pattern is similar to `(*PRUNE)`, except that on failure it also signifies that whatever text that was matched leading up to the `(*SKIP)` pattern being executed cannot be part of *any* match of this pattern.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This effectively means that the regex engine "skips" forward to this position on failure and tries to match again, (assuming that there is sufficient room to match).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The name of the `(*SKIP:*NAME*)` pattern has special significance.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] If a `(*MARK:*NAME*)` was encountered while matching, then it is that position which is used as the "skip point".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] If no `(*MARK)` of that name was encountered, then the `(*SKIP)` operator has no effect.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] When used without a name the "skip point" is where the match point was when executing the `(*SKIP)` pattern.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Once the 'aaab' at the start of the string has matched, and the `(*SKIP)` executed, the next starting point will be where the cursor was when the `(*SKIP)` was executed.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This zero-width pattern can be used to mark the point reached in a string when a certain part of the pattern has been successfully matched.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] A later `(*SKIP)` pattern will then skip forward to that point if backtracked into on failure.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Any number of `(*MARK)` patterns are allowed, and the *NAME* portion may be duplicated.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] In addition to interacting with the `(*SKIP)` pattern, `(*MARK:*NAME*)` can be used to "label" a pattern branch, so that after matching, the program can determine which branches of the pattern were involved in the match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] When a match is successful, the `$REGMARK` variable will be set to the name of the most recently executed `(*MARK:*NAME*)` that was involved in the match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This can be used to determine which branch of a pattern was matched without using a separate capture group for each branch, which in turn can result in a performance improvement, as perl cannot optimize `/(?:(x)|(y)|(z))/` as efficiently as something like `/(?:x(*MARK:x)|y(*MARK:y)|z(*MARK:z))/`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] When a match has failed, and unless another verb has been involved in failing the match and has provided its own name to use, the `$REGERROR` variable will be set to the name of the most recently executed `(*MARK:*NAME*)`.
