[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Regular expressions provide a terse and powerful programming language.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] As with most other power tools, power comes together with the ability to wreak havoc.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The `o?` matches at the beginning of "`foo`", and since the position in the string is not moved by the match, `o?` would match again and again because of the `"*"` quantifier.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] However, long experience has shown that many programming tasks may be significantly simplified by using repeated subexpressions that may match zero-length substrings.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Thus Perl allows such constructs, by *forcefully breaking the infinite loop*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The rules for this are different for lower-level loops given by the greedy quantifiers `*+{}`, and for higher-level ones like the `/g` modifier or `split()` operator.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The lower-level loops are *interrupted* (that is, the loop is broken) when Perl detects that a repeated expression matched a zero-length substring.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Notice that "hello" is only printed once, as when Perl sees that the sixth iteration of the outermost `(?:)*` matches a zero-length string, it stops the `"*"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The higher-level loops preserve an additional state between iterations: whether the last match was zero-length.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] To break the loop, the following match after a zero-length match is prohibited to have a length of zero.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This prohibition interacts with backtracking (see "Backtracking"), and so the *second best* match is chosen if the *best* match is of zero length.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] At each position of the string the best match given by non-greedy `??` is the zero-length match, and the *second best* match is what is matched by `\w`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Thus zero-length matches alternate with one-character-long matches.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Similarly, for repeated `m/()/g` the second-best match is the match at the position one notch further in the string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The additional state of being *matched with zero-length* is associated with the matched string, and is reset by each assignment to `pos()`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Zero-length matches at the end of the previous match are ignored during `split`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Each of the elementary pieces of regular expressions which were described before (such as `ab` or `\Z`) could match at most one substring at the given position of the input string.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] However, in a typical regular expression these elementary pieces are combined into more complicated patterns using combining operators `ST`, `S|T`, `S*` *etc*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] (in these examples `"S"` and `"T"` are regular subexpressions).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Such combinations can include alternatives, leading to a problem of choice: if we match a regular expression `a|ab` against `"abc"`, will it match substring `"a"` or `"ab"`?
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] One way to describe which substring is actually matched is the concept of backtracking (see "Backtracking").
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] However, this description is too low-level and makes you think in terms of a particular implementation.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Another description starts with notions of "better"/"worse".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] All the substrings which may be matched by the given regular expression can be sorted from the "best" match to the "worst" match, and it is the "best" match which is chosen.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This substitutes the question of "what is chosen?" by the question of "which matches are better, and which are worse?".
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Again, for elementary pieces there is no such question, since at most one match at a given position is possible.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] This section describes the notion of better/worse for combining operators.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] In the description below `"S"` and `"T"` are regular subexpressions.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Consider two possible matches, `AB` and `A'B'`, `"A"` and `A'` are substrings which can be matched by `"S"`, `"B"` and `B'` are substrings which can be matched by `"T"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] If `"A"` is a better match for `"S"` than `A'`, `AB` is a better match than `A'B'`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] If `"A"` and `A'` coincide: `AB` is a better match than `AB'` if `"B"` is a better match for `"T"` than `B'`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] When `"S"` can match, it is a better match than when only `"T"` can match.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Ordering of two matches for `"S"` is the same as for `"S"`.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Matches as `SSS...S` (repeated as many times as necessary).
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Matches the best match for `"S"` and only that.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Only the best match for `"S"` is considered.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] For this grouping operator there is no need to describe the ordering, since only whether or not `"S"` can match is important.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The ordering is the same as for the regular expression which is the result of *EXPR*, or the pattern contained by capture group *PARNO*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] Recall that which of *yes-pattern* or *no-pattern* actually matches is already determined.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The ordering of the matches is the same as for the chosen subexpression.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] The above recipes describe the ordering of matches *at a given position*.
[src:perl-docs/perlre-p04] One more rule is needed to understand how a match is determined for the whole regular expression: a match at an earlier position is always better than a match at a later position.
