[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Like many languages, Perl provides for user-defined subroutines.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] These may be located anywhere in the main program, loaded in from other files via the `do`, `require`, or `use` keywords, or generated on the fly using `eval` or anonymous subroutines.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] You can even call a function indirectly using a variable containing its name or a CODE reference.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] The Perl model for function call and return values is simple: all functions are passed as parameters one single flat list of scalars, and all functions likewise return to their caller one single flat list of scalars.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Any arrays or hashes in these call and return lists will collapse, losing their identities--but you may always use pass-by-reference instead to avoid this.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Both call and return lists may contain as many or as few scalar elements as you'd like.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] In a subroutine that uses signatures (see "Signatures" below), arguments are assigned into lexical variables introduced by the signature.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] In the current implementation of Perl they are also accessible in the `@_` array in the same way as for non-signature subroutines, but accessing them in this manner is now discouraged inside such a signature-using subroutine.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] In a subroutine that does not use signatures, any arguments passed in show up in the array `@_`.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Therefore, if you called a function with two arguments, those would be stored in `$_[0]` and `$_[1]`.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] The array `@_` is a local array, but its elements are aliases for the actual scalar parameters.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] In particular, if an element `$_[0]` is updated, the corresponding argument is updated (or an error occurs if it is not updatable).
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] If an argument is an array or hash element which did not exist when the function was called, that element is created only when (and if) it is modified or a reference to it is taken.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] (Some earlier versions of Perl created the element whether or not the element was assigned to.) Assigning to the whole array `@_` removes that aliasing, and does not update any arguments.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] When not using signatures, Perl does not otherwise provide a means to create named formal parameters.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] In practice all you do is assign to a `my()` list of these.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Variables that aren't declared to be private are global variables.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] For gory details on creating private variables, see "Private Variables via my()" and "Temporary Values via local()".
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] To create protected environments for a set of functions in a separate package (and probably a separate file), see "Packages" in perlmod.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] A `return` statement may be used to exit a subroutine, optionally specifying the returned value, which will be evaluated in the appropriate context (list, scalar, or void) depending on the context of the subroutine call.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] If you specify no return value, the subroutine returns an empty list in list context, the undefined value in scalar context, or nothing in void context.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] If you return one or more aggregates (arrays and hashes), these will be flattened together into one large indistinguishable list.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] If no `return` is found and if the last statement is an expression, its value is returned.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] If the last statement is a loop control structure like a `foreach` or a `while`, the returned value is unspecified.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Because the assignment copies the values, this also has the effect of turning call-by-reference into call-by-value.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Otherwise a function is free to do in-place modifications of `@_` and change its caller's values.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] You aren't allowed to modify constants in this way, of course.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] If an argument were actually literal and you tried to change it, you'd take a (presumably fatal) exception.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Notice how this (unprototyped) function doesn't care whether it was passed real scalars or arrays.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Perl sees all arguments as one big, long, flat parameter list in `@_`.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] This is one area where Perl's simple argument-passing style shines.
[src:perl-docs/perlsub-p01] Like the flattened incoming parameter list, the return list is also flattened on return.
